se}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68174"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is admitted to hospital for a total laparoscopic hysterectomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy for adenomyosis. She has completed her family and has no significant medical history. She takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. During the procedure, the surgeon is identifying the relevant vascular pedicles required to perform a safe oophorectomy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most accurately describes the origin of the ovarian artery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["External iliac artery","Internal iliac artery","Common iliac artery","Renal artery","Abdominal aorta"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the origin and course of the ovarian artery is crucial for safe laparoscopic oophorectomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal aorta\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. The ovarian arteries arise directly from the anterior surface of the abdominal aorta at the level of L2, below the renal arteries. They travel retroperitoneally within the infundibulopelvic ligament to reach the ovary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInternal iliac artery\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While the internal iliac artery gives rise to the uterine artery, which provides some blood supply to the ovary via anastomotic branches, it is not the origin of the ovarian artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExternal iliac artery\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The external iliac artery does not give rise to the ovarian artery. It continues as the femoral artery below the inguinal ligament.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal artery\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While the ovarian arteries arise at approximately the same vertebral level as the renal arteries, they are separate direct branches from the aorta.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommon iliac artery\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The common iliac artery does not give rise to the ovarian artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring surgery, careful identification of the retroperitoneal structures is essential. The ureter runs close to the infundibulopelvic ligament and must be identified to prevent injury. Both the infundibulopelvic ligament containing the ovarian vessels and the utero-ovarian ligament containing anastomotic vessels must be separately ligated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The ovarian artery is a direct branch of the abdominal aorta at the level of L2.","Safe laparoscopic oophorectomy requires careful identification and separate ligation of both the infundibulopelvic ligament and utero-ovarian ligament.","The ureter runs retroperitoneally close to the infundibulopelvic ligament and must be identified to prevent injury."],"references":["Chaudhry R, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis: Uterine Arteries. [Updated 2023 Sep 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482267/#"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53631"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16995"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53631"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T14:21:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T14:22:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9685"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68174"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"des